[32m│[0m ## thoughts                                                                  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m This was a straightforward authentication bypass challenge. The key insight  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m was that the JavaScript validation in the login form was purely client-side: [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m ```javascript                                                                [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m function funcion_login(){                                                    [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m     if (document.form.password.value=='sup3rsecr3t' &&                       [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m document.form.username.value=='admin'){                                      [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m         document.form.submit();                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m     }                                                                        [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m }                                                                            [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m ```                                                                          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m The credentials were hardcoded in the client-side JavaScript, making them    [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m visible to anyone who inspects the page source. By sending a direct POST     [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m request with curl (bypassing the JavaScript), we successfully authenticated  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m and received the flag immediately in the response.                           [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m The application appears to only have `/index.php` as a valid endpoint - all  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m other common paths returned 404 errors. The flag was embedded directly in    [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m the HTML response upon successful authentication, requiring no further       [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m enumeration or exploitation.                                                 [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m This demonstrates a common web security anti-pattern: relying on client-side [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m validation for authentication and exposing sensitive credentials in          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m client-accessible code.                                                      [32m│[0m
